<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Startup Registration Criteria</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles/startupCriteria.css" />
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="container">
      <header>
        <h1>Startup Registration Criteria</h1>
      </header>
      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>1. Entity Type</h2>
        <p>
          To be eligible for registration under the Startup India scheme, the
          entity should be registered as a private limited company, limited
          liability partnership (LLP), or partnership firm. Sole proprietorship
          firms and public limited companies are not eligible for registration
          under the scheme.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>2. Age Criteria</h2>
        <p>
          The startup should not be more than 10 years old from the date of
          incorporation. However, for startups in the biotechnology sector, the
          age limit is extended to 15 years.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>3. Turnover Limit</h2>
        <p>
          The turnover of the startup should not exceed Rs. 100 crore in any of
          the previous financial years. Startups that exceed this turnover limit
          are not eligible for registration under the scheme.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>4. Innovation Criteria</h2>
        <p>
          The startup should be working towards innovation, development,
          deployment, or commercialization of a new product, process, or service
          driven by technology or intellectual property. Startups that are
          replicating existing business models are not eligible for registration
          under the scheme.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>5. Certification</h2>
        <p>
          To register under the Startup India scheme, the startup should have
          obtained a certificate of recognition from the Department for
          Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade (DPIIT). The certificate is
          issued based on self-certification and can be obtained by submitting
          an online application on the Startup India portal.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>6. Compliance Criteria</h2>
        <p>
          The startup should comply with all legal requirements such as the
          Companies Act, Income Tax Act, and Goods and Services Tax Act. The
          startup should also have a bank account in the name of the business
          and provide the details of the same during registration.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>7. Funding Criteria</h2>
        <p>
          The startup should not have received funding from any other scheme of
          the Government of India. However, startups that have received funding
          from family and friends or angel investors are eligible for
          registration under the scheme.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="criteria-section">
        <h2>8. Job Creation</h2>
        <p>
          The startup should aim to create jobs or have the potential to create
          jobs in the future. The scheme encourages startups that create
          employment opportunities in the country.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
